    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>May 3 | 1875.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Paget</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for your kind present of your Lectures. From their titles I feel sure that they will, like all your other writings which I have read, interest me greatly.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>The vivisection question seems to be going on in every way as well as c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be desired.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>My dear Paget | yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Paget’s <hi rend="italic">Clinical lectures and essays</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8724.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Paget 1875</ref>) contained sixteen essays, fifteen of which had already been published in medical journals or hospital reports. There is an annotated copy of Paget’s <hi rend="italic">Lectures on surgical pathology</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6139.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Paget 1853</ref>) in Darwin Library–CUL, and a copy of the third edition of this work in Darwin Library–Down (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 658–61).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Paget had given his support for a vivisection bill prepared by CD and his friends to be presented to Parliament (see letter to from J. S. Burdon Sanderson, 30 April [1875].</note>
        </div>        
            
